@HeathieJ 

"The Lone Ranger" and "Gunsmoke" were radio programs for us.  AFN (the Armed Forces Network) broadcast those on Saturday mornings...ah, those thrilling days of yesteryear, hearing Rossini's "William Tell" trumpet part....  

We did not have a television until 1958.  I don't recall seeing the program then, but there was a series called "The Gray Ghost" about a Confederate 'hero' (?Francis Marion?) that was very popular in Arkansas....where we were stationed at the time....(one whole month before we were packed out and on our way to Hawaii, where TV was only available via  tape..  I think we were too old for Lone Ranger, but Huckleberry Hound was a lot of fun.)

@Mean Old Lady 

the Gray Ghost was John Singleton Mosby, a Confederate ranger whose guerrilla band frequently attacked and disrupted Union supply lines in Virginia and Maryland during the American Civil War. After a raid, he'd disappear into the fog, helped by the camouflage of his gray uniform.

Francis Marion was the Swamp Fox, known for his guerilla-type tactics in the Revolutionary War. I think a lot of his exploits were in southern Virginia near Norfolk, around the Great Dismal Swamp.

@HeathieJ I grew up with VHS already in the house but Annie was one of my first tapes too. I watched it so many times on repeat that I wore out the tape and we had to get a new copy!

To this day, there is still a large collection of VHS tapes at home, many of which are home videos and kid tapes like Disney sing along songs, that I would love to play if we could get our hands on a player that works again. 

We also had a LaserDisc player in my dad’s office waiting room for a while, but we never had too many things we could play on that one.

